  <main id="main-content" class="page-shell">
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="hero-layout">
        <div>
          <div class="hero-tagline"><span class="hero-tagline-dot"></span>Vision</div>
          <h1 class="hero-heading">A readiness layer Japan can rely on.</h1>
          <p class="hero-sub">
            TASK L3C exists to strengthen disaster readiness in Japan before the next major event —
            by funding and connecting trusted frontline NGOs and NPOs.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="card-surface">
      <section class="section">
        <header class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">What TASK is</div><h2>Readiness, not response</h2></header>
        <p>
          Japan’s disaster response is strong. The weakness is what happens before the ground shakes:
          stable readiness funding, mapped mutual‑aid roles, and clear international support lanes.
          TASK L3C builds that missing layer.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <header class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">Primary missions</div><h2>Support without distraction</h2></header>
        <p>
          Every organization has its own primary mission. TASK strengthens readiness while protecting that mission,
          so partners can serve communities every day and still surge safely during disasters.
        </p>
        <p>
          TASK operates under our parent company, <strong>New Wind Therapeutics L3C</strong>, which maintains a separate primary mission.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section founder-band">
        <header class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">Founder</div><h2>Carl Harold Williams</h2></header>
        <p>
          TASK builds on decades of embedded emergency management work in Japan, including self‑deployment
          after 3/11 and long‑term partnerships across Tohoku and Fukushima.
        </p>
